.TH GENAPP "8" "May 2026" "Genapp 1.0.0" "System Administration Utilities"
.SH NAME
Genapp \- shell-api
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B genapp
\fI\,OPTIONS <application name>\/\fR
.PP
Arguments:
.TP
<application name>
a word identifying the app, starting with an uppercase (will be enforced)
.PP
OPTIONS:
.TP
\fB\-\-verbose\fR
Verbose mode
.TP
\fB\-\-email\fR =<TEXTE>
app's official contact email
.TP
\fB\-\-help\fR, \fB\-h\fR
Displays app usage
.TP
\fB\-y\fR
Assume 'Yes' when prompted for confirmation
.TP
\fB\-\-github\-id\fR =<TEXTE>
User id to use to build the github URL for the debian package homepage definition
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Displays the app version
.HP
\fB\-\-root\-release\-dir\fR =<FOLDER PATH> Path to the root folder where are stored software release
.TP
\fB\-\-author\fR =<TEXTE>
Author of the app
.TP
\fB\-\-desc\fR =<TEXTE>
Description of the app
.TP
\fB\-\-http\fR =<URL>
URL for the debian package homepage of the app
.TP
\fB\-\-man\fR
Displays the manual page
.SH DESCRIPTION
Genapp tool generates shell script app skeletons based the shell\-api library. The generated skeletons are immediately operational and just need to be
adapted to the specific app to be implemented. It will generate the following files:
.PP
\- COPYRIGHT.txt
.PP
\- LICENSE.txt: MIT by default, to be replaced if necessary
.PP
\- CHANGELOG.txt: to be filled out as versions are released
.PP
\- EXAMPLES: a template
.PP
\- <yourapp>__options.sh: skeleton file for managing options, by default includes \fB\-h\fR|\-\-help, \fB\-\-man\fR, \fB\-v\fR|\-\-version, \fB\-\-verbose\fR, \fB\-y\fR
.PP
\- <yourapp>__help.h: skeleton file providing help functions to enable packaging with dpkg
.PP
\- <yourapp>__vars.h: skeleton file (empty) to be used for providing app\-specific global variable definitions
.PP
\- <yourapp>: application skeleton, including all the above ones
.PP
\- pack/debian/control : for packaging with dpkg
.SH EXAMPLES
Generating a test app
.IP
# An app named 'TestApp' is generated, inside folder 'testapp', main script will be 'testapp'. The root output folder for any app release is '..', relatively to the app source dir. The home page URL for the app will be https://github/michelm33/testapp
.IP
genapp TestApp \-y \-\-author="George Washington" \-\-email="george.washington@whitehouse.org" \-\-desc="A test application" \-\-github\-id="michelm33" \-\-root\-release\-dir="../release"
.IP
# Same as previous example, but the home page URL for the app is explicitely defind as 'https://slashetc/testapp'
.IP
genapp TestApp \-y \-\-author="George Washington" \-\-email="george.washington@whitehouse.org" \-\-desc="A test application" \-\-http="https://slashetc/testapp" \-\-root\-release\-dir="../release"
.PP
Generating a debian package
.IP
# 'TestApp' is the generated app. This generates a release file tree and a debian package
.IP
make release
.PP
Generating the man pages
.IP
# 'TestApp' is the generated app. This generates the manpage which can be open using 'man testapp'
.IP
make man
.IP
man testapp
.PP
Executing the generated app
.IP
# 'TestApp' is the generated app
.IP
\&./testapp
.PP
Showing the app help
.IP
# 'TestApp' is the generated app
.IP
\&./testapp \-h
.PP
Showing the files managed by the app
.IP
# 'TestApp' is the generated app
.IP
\&./testapp \-\-files
